\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Measure Theory Homework 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable if and only if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,q)$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable, then certainly 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (and hence for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

).
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,q)\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c<q_{n}<c+\frac{1}{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Such a choice for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 can be made since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(-\infty,c]=\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}f^{-1}(-\infty,q_{n})
\]

\end_inset

To see this, first note that the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(-\infty,c]\subseteq\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}f^{-1}(-\infty,q_{n})
\]

\end_inset

is clear since each 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,q_{n})$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $c<q_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 For the reverse inclusion, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}f^{-1}(-\infty,q_{n})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)<q_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}\to c$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\leq c$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(-\infty,c]$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that we needed to use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 in order to prove this.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we answer this problem, we give a more general definition of what
 it means for a function to be measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we show that this more general definition is equivalent to the definition
 we've been using when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 is the Borel 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defnmeasurabled}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{N})$
\end_inset

 be measurable spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathcal{N})\subseteq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(\mathcal{N})=\{f^{-1}(B)\mid B\in\mathcal{N}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(B)=\{x\in X\mid f(x)\in B\}\in\mathcal{M}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

, then we will just say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 are clear from context, then we will just say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us now show that when 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, that this definition is equivalent to the definition we gave in class.
 We first prove the following two propositions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{equivalentdefofmeasurable}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{N})$
\end_inset

 be measurable spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 is generated as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra by the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathcal{N})\subseteq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathcal{C})\subseteq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is clear, so we just prove the other direction.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathcal{C})\subseteq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{B\in\mathcal{P}(Y)\mid f^{-1}(B)\in\mathcal{M}\}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 maps the emptyset set to the emptyset and maps the whole space 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to the whole space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 commutes with unions and complements.
 Furthemore, this 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathcal{C})\subseteq\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
smallest 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{N}\subseteq\{B\in\mathcal{P}(Y)\mid f^{-1}(B)\in\mathcal{M}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(B)\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propborelsigmaalgebragen}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\{(-\infty,c)\mid c\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})=\sigma(\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the collection of all subintervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $[n,n+1)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{n}=\sigma(\mathcal{I}_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})=\{E\subseteq\mathbb{R}\mid E\cap[n,n+1)\in\mathcal{B}_{n}\text{ for all }n\in\mathbb{Z}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,c)\cap[n,n+1]$
\end_inset

 is a subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $[n,n+1]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\mathcal{C})\subseteq\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
smallest 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

).
 Conversely, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

 contains all subintervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $[n,n+1)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\mathcal{C})\supseteq\mathcal{B}_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
smallest 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra which contains all subintervals of 
\begin_inset Formula $[n,n+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})=\sigma\left(\bigcup_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{B}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})\subseteq\sigma(\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corequivdefofmeas}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M})$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propborelsigmaalgebragen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{equivalentdefofmeasurable})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M})$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the Borel 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is a collection of sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})\subseteq\sigma(\mathcal{C})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(C)\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{equivalentdefofmeasurable})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corequivdefofmeas})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.i
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $q,r\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{1/n}(q)=\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid|x-q|<1/n\}
\]

\end_inset

Then the collection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{B}=\{\mathrm{B}_{1/n}(q)\mid n\in\mathbb{N}\text{ and }q\in\mathbb{Q}\}
\]

\end_inset

forms a countable basis for the usual topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as a union of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}B_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\lambda}\in\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 and where the index set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
countable.

\emph default
 In particular, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{B})\subseteq\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\mathscr{B})$
\end_inset

 is the usual Euclidean topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus since 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

 can be expressed a countable union of open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (by definition of what it means to be continuous, the inverse image of
 an open set under 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is open).
 Since every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is Borel measurable, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.ii
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a monotone increasing function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

-measurable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\neq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $c\leq f(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)<c\leq f(y),
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq y$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is monotone increasing.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty and bounded above, it follows that its supremum exists.
 Denote its supremum by 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{0}=\sup\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid f(x)<c\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(-\infty,c)=\begin{cases}
(-\infty,y_{0}) & \text{if }f(y_{0})\geq c\\
(-\infty,y_{0}] & \text{if }f(y_{0})<c.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

, it must be greater than or equal to all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\subseteq\begin{cases}
(-\infty,y_{0}) & \text{if }f(y_{0})\geq c\\
(-\infty,y_{0}] & \text{if }f(y_{0})<c.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(-\infty,y_{0})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not an upper bound of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
least 
\emph default
upper bound), which means that there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x')<c$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\leq f(x')$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)<c$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(-\infty,c)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\supseteq\begin{cases}
(-\infty,y_{0}) & \text{if }f(y_{0})\geq c\\
(-\infty,y_{0}] & \text{if }f(y_{0})<c.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

In any case, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(-\infty,c)\in\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)$
\end_inset

 be a measure space.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n}\colon X\to[0,\infty])$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of non-negative measurable functions.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}f_{n}(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a non-negative measurable function and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{N}=\sum_{n=1}^{N}f_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{N}$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}f_{n}(x)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}f_{n}(x)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}s_{N}(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{N}$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative measurable function since it is a finite sum of nonnegative
 measurable functions, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{N})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of nonnegative functions which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative measurable function.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{N}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence since if 
\begin_inset Formula $M\leq N$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{M}(x) & =\sum_{n=1}^{M}f_{n}(x)\\
 & \leq\sum_{n=1}^{N}f_{n}(x)\\
 & =s_{N}(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, where the inequality follows from the fact that each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative.
 Therefore we may apply the Monotone Convergence Theorem to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\int_{X}s_{N}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\int_{X}\sum_{n=1}^{N}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we obtained the third line from the fourth line from the fact that
 this is a finite sum.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)$
\end_inset

 be measure space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon X\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 be a nonnegative measurable function.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}\colon\mathcal{M}\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{g}(E)=\int_{X}g1_{E}\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is a measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu_{g}(\emptyset) & =\int_{X}g1_{\emptyset}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}g\cdot0\cdot\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}0\cdot\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}$
\end_inset

 is finitely additive.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})_{n=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 be a finite sequence of pairwise disjoint sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu_{g}\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}\right) & =\int_{X}g1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}g\sum_{n=1}^{N}1_{E_{n}}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}\sum_{n=1}^{N}g1_{E_{n}}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{N}\int_{X}g1_{E_{n}}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{N}\nu_{g}(E_{n}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that each 
\begin_inset Formula $g1_{E_{n}}$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative measurable function in order to commute the finite sum
 with the integral.
 Thus it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}$
\end_inset

 is finitely additive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}$
\end_inset

 is countably subadditive.
 In problem 3 in HW4, we showed that for any nonnegative simple function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon X\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\varphi}\colon\mathcal{M}\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{\varphi}(E)=\int_{X}\varphi1_{E}\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset

is a measure.
 We will use this fact in what follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Choose an increasing sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n}\colon X\to[0,\infty])$
\end_inset

 of nonnegative simple functions which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 (we can do this since 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative measurable function).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n}1_{E})$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence of nonnegative simple functions which converges
 pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $g1_{E}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the Monotone Convergence Theorem that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu_{\varphi_{n}}(E) & =\int_{X}\varphi_{n}1_{E}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & \to\int_{X}g1_{E}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\nu_{g}(E)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, we can find a 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{E,\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 (which depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{g}(E)<\nu_{\varphi_{n}}(E)+\varepsilon\label{eq:ineqfdskl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N_{E,\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 However we will don't need estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}(E)$
\end_inset

 to this level of precision.
 We just need to know thta for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:ineqfdskl})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{k})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of measurable sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{g}\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty}E_{k}\right)<\nu_{\varphi_{n}}\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty}E_{k}\right)+\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu_{g}\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty}E_{k}\right) & \leq\nu_{\varphi_{n}}\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty}E_{k}\right)+\varepsilon\\
 & \leq\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\nu_{\varphi_{n}}(E_{k})+\varepsilon\\
 & \leq\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\nu_{g}(E_{k})+\varepsilon
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we obtained the second line from the first line using countable subadditiv
ity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\varphi_{n}}$
\end_inset

, and where we obtained the third line from the second line from the fact
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}1_{E_{k}}\leq g1_{E_{k}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and from monotonicity of integration.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 gives us countable subadditivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)$
\end_inset

 be a measure space.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n}\colon X\to[0,\infty])$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing sequence of nonnegative measurable functions which converges
 pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{X}f_{1}\mathrm{d}\mu<\infty$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu=\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu.\label{eq:decseqcon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}=f_{n+1}-f_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing sequence, each 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative.
 Furthermore each 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

 is measurable since it is a difference of two measurable functions.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}g_{n}$
\end_inset

 and observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}g_{n}\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}g_{n}\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}(f_{n+1}-f_{n})\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}(f_{N}-f_{1})\\
 & =f-f_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows from problem 4 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu-\int_{X}f_{1}\mathrm{d}\mu & =\int_{X}(f-f_{1})\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\int_{X}g_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\int_{X}g_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\int_{X}(f_{n+1}-f_{n})\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\int_{X}\sum_{n=1}^{N}(f_{n+1}-f_{n})\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\int_{X}(f_{N}-f_{1})\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\int_{X}f_{N}\mathrm{d}\mu-\int_{X}f_{1}\mathrm{d}\mu.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{X}f_{1}\mathrm{d}\mu<0$
\end_inset

, we can cancel it from both sides to get 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:decseqcon})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fatou's Lemma remains valid if the hypothesis that all 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\colon X\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 are nonnegative measurable functions is replaced by the hypothesis that
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are measurable and there exists a nonnegative integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon X\to[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $-g\leq f_{n}$
\end_inset

 pointwise for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $(g+f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of nonnegative measurable functions which converges pointwise
 to the nonnegative measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g+f$
\end_inset

.
 Then it follows from Fatou's Lemma that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu & =\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}((g+f)-g)\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}(g+f)\mathrm{d}\mu-\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\int_{X}(g+f)\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & \leq\liminf_{n\to\infty}\int_{X}(g+f_{n})\mathrm{d}\mu\\
 & =\liminf_{n\to\infty}(\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}(g+f_{n})\mathrm{d}\mu-\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu)\\
 & =\liminf_{n\to\infty}(\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}((g+f_{n})-g)\mathrm{d}\mu)\\
 & =\liminf_{n\to\infty}(\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu)\\
 & =\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu+\liminf_{n\to\infty}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{X}g\mathrm{d}\mu<\infty$
\end_inset

, we can cancel it from both sides to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu\leq\liminf_{n\to\infty}\int_{X}f_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 8
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Compute the following integrals
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{\sin(x/n)}{(1+x/n)^{n}}\mathrm{d}x\label{eq:integral1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{1+nx^{2}}{(1+x^{2})^{n}}\mathrm{d}x\label{eq:integral2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first compute 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integral1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}=\sin(x/n)(1+x/n)^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is measurable since each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is continuous (the denominator is only zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-n$
\end_inset

).
 Let us check that each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is integrable: we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{\infty}|f_{n}|\mathrm{d}x & =\int_{0}^{\infty}\left|\frac{\sin(x/n)}{(1+x/n)^{n}}\right|\\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{\infty}\left|(1+x/n)^{-n}\right|\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =\int_{0}^{\infty}(1+x/n)^{-n}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-x}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is integrable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+x/n)^{n}\to e^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(x/n)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-x}\geq|f_{n}|$
\end_inset

 pointwise and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-x}$
\end_inset

 is integrable (
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}|e^{-x}|\mathrm{d}x=1$
\end_inset

).
 It follows from the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{\sin(x/n)}{(1+x/n)^{n}}\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{\infty}0\mathrm{d}x=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we compute 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integral2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}=(1+nx^{2})(1+x^{2})^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is measurable since each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is continuous (the denominator is never zero for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative (since taking squares makes everything nonnegative).
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing sequence.
 Indeed
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{f_{n}}{f_{n+1}} & =\left(\frac{1+nx^{2}}{(1+x^{2})^{n}}\right)\left(\frac{(1+x^{2})^{n+1}}{1+(n+1)x^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{(1+nx^{2})(1+x^{2})}{1+(n+1)x^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{nx^{4}+(n+1)x^{2}+1}{(n+1)x^{2}+1}\\
 & \geq\frac{(n+1)x^{2}+1}{(n+1)x^{2}+1}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing sequence which is bounded below, so it must converge pointwise
 to some function.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, it's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(0)\to0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

, we use L'Hopital's rule to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n} & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{1+nx^{2}}{(1+x^{2})^{n}}\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{x^{2}}{\ln(1+x^{2})(1+x^{2})^{n}}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}f_{1}\mathrm{d}x & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{1+x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =1\\
 & <\infty,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

it follows from problem 6 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{1+nx^{2}}{(1+x^{2})^{n}}\mathrm{d}x & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_{0}^{1}f_{n}\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}0\mathrm{d}x\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

